ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='I found an issue in age-calculator.spec.ts: the leap year test says "
On 2024-02-28, born 2000-02-29 -> 23 years old" but if someone was born on Feb 2
9, 2000, on Feb 28, 2024 they would be 23 (turning 24 on Feb 29, 2024). Wait, 20
24 is a leap year, so Feb 29 exists. The test sets the time to Feb 28, so they h
aven\'t had their birthday yet in 2024. 2024 - 2000 = 24, but since it\'s Feb 28
and their birthday is Feb 29, they should be 23. The test expects 23, which is c
orrect. But the comment is a bit misleading because in a leap year (2024), Feb 2
9 does exist, and the birthday would be the next day.\n\nActually wait, the `cal
culateAge` function uses `getUTCDate()` which returns the day of the month. For 
Feb 29, 2000, `getUTCDate()` returns 29. For Feb 28, 2024, `getUTCDate()` return
s 28. So `dayDiff = 28 - 29 = -1 < 0`, so age is decremented. 24 - 1 = 23. Corre
ct.\n\nBut there\'s a real bug in `calculateAge`: it doesn\'t handle leap year b
irthdays when the current year is NOT a leap year. For example, if someone is bo
rn on Feb 29, 2000, on March 1, 2023 (non-leap year), `getUTCDate()` for birthDa
te returns 29, for now returns 1. `monthDiff = 2 - 2 = 0`, `dayDiff = 1 - 29 = -
28 < 0`, age decremented. 2023 - 2000 = 23, minus 1 = 22. But on March 1, 2023, 
they should be 23 (their birthday in non-leap years is March 1). This is a known
edge case that the test doesn\'t cover.\n\nLet me check more files. I need to lo
ok at:\n- packages/design-system\n- tests/jest.config.bdd.js\n- tests/bdd/ featu
re files and step definitions\n- .github/workflows/design-check.yml\n- Various m
issing files\n\nLet me also check the data-source.ts and database config.',
    encrypted=None
)
